social_posts.post_text: The San Francisco Pas Normal Store is open. It took an immense amount of work from the entire team make this happen. Come hang out, ride, relax, and say hi.
Good feels getting out on a quick winter spin with some dad legs.
2022 was alright! Ready for what’s next. ✌🏼

To be completely honest, it’s a strange relationship— the narrative of my career with Specialized has undoubtedly had its up’s and downs. It’s not only how Specialized managed the recent departure of the global ambassador program, but also a few turbulent experiences throughout my career with the company. I’m still mentally processing… I love bikes. I really love these bikes. Yes, I’m parting ways and selling a few of my bikes right now, but no, I’m not purging to provoke a middle finger and no, I’m not jumping onto the next bus of sponsors. This industry only works if we take care of the relationships we value. I’m not saying yes or no, let’s just ride bikes.

Before the grand opening, a small group of US ambassadors rode from the @pasnormalstudios SF flagship store to Sonoma during the wettest month for the state in decades. What a way to kick off the year. #destinationeverywhere @pasnormalstudios @internationalcyclingclub photo: @dominiquepowers

This is a race format I am looking forward to. Inspired by my years with @mashsf, this is a simplified alleycat, mixed with a shorter version brevet. It’s an extremely adaptable and easy format that lets people push without excuses. 

70 miles, one checkpoint and back to the start. No routes, no teams. Checkpoint announced before the start.

Destination Everywhere kicks off in LA. @raylynnuss is at the helm this year traveling across the US. Lots of old friends and new. Thanks for the hospitality @properjay and @luftlosangeles see you again soon!

I like this bike so much I think it deserves a spot on the archive (posts). It was pretty fun to digitize and remaster the original Merz logos. @eriknohlin finessed the details and dialed in the colors. There were only 200 of these made, this was number 4.
15 people joined a 100+ mile ride to Sonoma and catch a ferry home. We had to add a few wildcard moments in there. Lots of sun, gummies, beers, and tacos.

I’ve been dealing with a pinched lower back for almost two years. It ebbs and flows every few months getting better and worse. I’m finally starting to feel slightly like a human again. Time to take it seriously this time and find some real help for my back while it works, build some structure around workouts and stretching. Getting old? Dad-bod? Maybe both?

I think one of the hardest parts about recovering from an injury is consistency. You’re effectively starting from scratch while you still have the mentality of when you were strong of which your no where near. Small gains can be tough to accept. But I’ve pushed myself to be consistent with some trainer time in the evening followed by stretching and strengthening. For contrast, 30 days ago spinning the pedals wasn’t an option.

Spent some time in NYC a few weeks back. We did a few rides, all of which were hot, rain or shine. Had a great time riding and connecting with some new and old friends. Looking forward to getting out there again. ✌🏼

@pasnormalstudios @internationalcyclingclub

Have I run at all in the last 2 years? Nope
Do my legs hurt? Yes

But I had a lot of fun last night running in the park with a bunch of friends. I’ll let you know if I can walk by Friday ⚰️🏃🏻‍♂️
